# 5. Market Data Layer

Primary data source:

Binance API

Used for:
- current prices
- 24h statistics
- candlestick chart data
- volume

Shared services:

getCurrentPrices()
getChartData()
getTopMovers()
getRecentNews()

Rules:

• Do not fetch market data directly in components
• Always use shared services
• All market data must go through internal API routes

---

# 6. Database Schema

Database: Supabase (Postgres)

Tables:

assets
market_snapshots
news_items
narratives
narrative_news
market_briefs
ai_runs
eval_runs

Vector embeddings:

pgvector

Used for:

• news embeddings
• narrative embeddings
• historical similarity search

---

# 7. AI Workflow Layer

All AI logic must live inside:

/ai/workflows

Examples:

market-brief.ts
token-analysis.ts
ask-market.ts
narrative-detection.ts

Shared runner:

runAIWorkflow()

Responsibilities:

• execute prompts
• validate structured outputs
• retry on failure
• fallback models
• log traces in Langfuse

---

# 8. Multi-Agent System

Agents:

Market Data Agent
News Agent
Narrative Agent
Risk Agent
Historical Similarity Agent
Synthesizer Agent
Validator Agent

Orchestration:

LangGraph

Flow:

collect signals → agents analyze → synthesizer merges → validator checks output

---

# 9. RAG Retrieval Layer

Sources:

news archive
narrative history
historical market events
token-specific context

Retrieval strategies:

vector search
hybrid search
semantic similarity
reranking

Implementation tools:

LlamaIndex
LangChain retrievers

---

# 10. Model Routing

Models must not be hardcoded.

Routing strategy:

cheap model → classification
medium model → analysis
strong model → final reasoning

Providers:

OpenRouter
Ollama
vLLM

---

# 11. Semantic Caching

Repeated prompts should be cached.

Examples:

Why is ETH pumping today?
What is driving ETH price today?
Why did ETH move up today?

These should resolve to the same cached response if context is unchanged.

---

# 12. Observability

All AI calls must be traced.

Tool:

Langfuse

Track:

tokens
latency
cost
prompt
response
workflow state

---

# 13. Coding Rules

Always:

• write TypeScript
• strongly type responses
• use Zod schemas for structured AI outputs
• centralize data access
• avoid duplicate logic
• implement retries for AI calls
• add logging

Never:

• call LLMs directly inside React components
• fetch market data inside UI components
• duplicate API logic

---

# 14. Testing Rules

Every new AI feature must include:

1. manual test checklist
2. structured output validation
3. error handling
4. Langfuse trace verification

Test scenarios:

• API success
• API failure
• invalid AI output
• retry logic
• caching behavior

